--- body ---
## Context
Ticket 0167 (PR #860) added `scripts/het_*.py` to this repo to generate a
figure for a paper that lives in the sibling repo `polycentric_activity`.
Documented in `architecture.md` (ticket 0169) as a deliberate call: reuse
this repo's OpenAlex-crawl/embedding conventions in place rather than
duplicate them there.

That reuse is a real Python import, not a copy: `het_build_corpus.py` does
`from utils import (...)`, `het_embed.py` does `from enrich_embeddings
import build_text` and `from utils import get_logger`. So the actual shape
of the dependency is: a paper's build pipeline, living in one git repo
(`polycentric_activity`), depends on internal, unpackaged modules
(`utils.py`, `enrich_embeddings.py`) of a *different* git repo
(`climate-finance-het`) that has no notion of being depended upon —
no version pin, no package boundary, no test coverage on the
`polycentric_activity` side that would catch a breaking refactor here.
`het_build_corpus.py`'s own tests live in *this* repo and only exercise
its own logic, not the contract with the paper that actually consumes the
figure.

The author flagged (2026-07-07): this may be the point where the shared
OpenAlex-crawl/embedding conventions (`retry_get`, `reconstruct_abstract`,
`build_text`, plus whatever `utils.py` exports) should be promoted out of
`climate-finance-het` into an independent, installable, reusable project —
something both repos (and any future one) depend on as a normal package,
rather than one repo's paper pipeline reaching into another repo's
`scripts/`. Author wants to think about this more before deciding — this
ticket tracks the question, not a plan to execute.

Precise statement of the smell (2026-07-09 review): there is **no live
cross-repo Python import today**. The `het_*.py` scripts physically live in
*this* repo and are run here; polycentric_activity references this repo only
by an absolute path to a data file (`data/het/seeds.csv`), not by import.
The `het_*.py` scripts are also **not in this repo's Makefile** — they are
orphan scripts. So the disease is not a fragile import contract (that only
materialises *after* a migration); it is that **paper B's build pipeline
squats in paper A's engine repo**. The cure is therefore relocation first,
sharing second — not sharing alone.

## Relevant files
- `scripts/utils.py`, `scripts/enrich_embeddings.py` — the modules
  `het_*.py` imports from
- `scripts/het_build_corpus.py`, `scripts/het_embed.py` — the importers
- `.claude/rules/architecture.md` §"Companion pipelines" — current
  (in-place-reuse) rationale, would need revision if this is acted on

## Decision (2026-07-08, revised 2026-07-09)
Clean up, not just extract. The clean end-state is **three moves**; the
2026-07-08 plan did only the middle one and would have left the smell in
place (see revision log). The open questions resolve as follows:

- **Recur?** Yes. The polycentric_activity HET figure work is growing
  (field swim-lane figure, Louvain community detection on the citation
  graph, venue→lane binning), each reusing the same OpenAlex-crawl and
  canonical-text conventions. The one-off assumption is void. (Caveat: the
  *growth* — community detection, venue binning — needs graph code, not the
  carved symbols; the shared surface itself is small and roughly stable at
  the five symbols below.)

- **Relocate?** Yes — this is the move that actually removes the smell.
  `het_build_corpus.py`, `het_embed.py`, `het_plot_overlap.py` are paper B's
  pipeline; they move to `polycentric_activity`. Nothing "companion" remains
  in this repo's `scripts/`. Extraction without relocation is strictly worse
  than today (a new package *plus* the same orphan scripts).

- **Boundary?** The OpenAlex-crawl + canonical-text layer — not the
  `pipeline_loaders` domain modules, not the embedding *model*. Five symbols:
  `retry_get`, `reconstruct_abstract`, `normalize_doi`, `build_text`, and
  `build_text`'s helper `is_boilerplate_abstract` (34 lines incl. its
  junk-phrase list — it rides along, the 2026-07-08 plan missed it).
  - `build_text` **is** in scope: het_embed uses a *different, cheaper*
    model (`paraphrase-multilingual-MiniLM-L12-v2`, its docstring says the
    vectors are not for quantitative claims), so the embedding spaces are
    deliberately non-comparable. What both pipelines share is the
    *model-agnostic canonical-text convention* ("what string represents a
    work"). Once the scripts live in different repos, that convention must be
    single-source — duplicating it reintroduces the silent drift we are
    killing.
  - `MAILTO`, `OPENALEX_API_KEY` are **out** — deployment config, not
    convention. The package functions take them as parameters; each repo
    supplies its own from its own `.env`. Shipping the constants couples the
    package to a particular env layout.
  - `get_logger` stays out; the package uses stdlib `logging.getLogger`.

- **Packaging / topology?** (Was deferred — now decided.) A `libs/openalex-corpus/`
  **path package inside THIS repo**, owned here because this is where the
  conventions originate. This repo depends on it via `[tool.uv.sources]`
  (already uses that block). `polycentric_activity` depends on it via **git
  source**, pinning a SHA. One source of truth, no third repo, skew is
  one-directional and visible. No PyPI.

## Measured facts (the carve-out surface and blast radius)
Where each symbol is **defined** (verified 2026-07-09), and its transitive deps:
- `retry_get` — `scripts/pipeline_io.py` — 13 files; carries `RETRY_MAX_RETRIES`
- `reconstruct_abstract` — `scripts/pipeline_text.py` — 5 files; pure, self-contained
- `normalize_doi` — `scripts/pipeline_text.py` (NOT utils.py — the 2026-07-08
  table was wrong; `utils.py` only re-exports it) — ~50 call sites; pure regex
- `build_text` — `scripts/enrich_embeddings.py` — 3 files; calls
  `is_boilerplate_abstract` (same module) → that helper + its junk-list move too
- `is_boilerplate_abstract` — `scripts/enrich_embeddings.py` — rides with build_text
- `get_logger` — `scripts/utils.py` — 159 files (LEFT in place)
- `MAILTO`, `OPENALEX_API_KEY` — `scripts/pipeline_io.py` — LEFT in place, injected

Key structural fact: **`utils.py` is already a re-export facade** — it imports
from `pipeline_io`/`pipeline_text`/`pipeline_loaders`/`pipeline_progress` and
re-exports (its docstring advertises `from utils import normalize_doi, ...`).
The het scripts import everything `from utils`, i.e. through the curated public
surface, not raw internals. This makes the shim strategy idiomatic here.

Third-party deps of the carved layer: `requests`, `numpy`, `pandas`. No torch
(the `torch`/`sentence_transformers` imports in `enrich_embeddings.py` are lazy,
inside a function, and stay out of scope).

Strategy to keep blast radius near zero: the extracted package becomes the
source of truth; the host modules (`pipeline_io.py`, `pipeline_text.py`,
`enrich_embeddings.py`) import the moved symbols FROM the package and
RE-EXPORT them; `utils.py`'s existing re-export chain is unchanged. So the
159/50/13/5/3 existing call sites keep their current `from utils import ...` /
`from pipeline_io import ...` imports. Only the definitions move; the shims
preserve the API. Precondition to verify at execution: each carved symbol is
self-contained enough that the host module → package direction has no cycle
back (confirmed for the pure functions; `build_text` needs `is_boilerplate_abstract`
moved with it).

## Actions
The three moves. (1) is the extraction; (2) is the relocation that actually
cures the smell; do NOT ship (1) without (2).

**Move A — extract the convention layer.**
1. Create `libs/openalex-corpus/` (path package in THIS repo). Move the
   *definitions* of `retry_get` (+ `RETRY_MAX_RETRIES`), `reconstruct_abstract`,
   `normalize_doi`, `build_text`, and `is_boilerplate_abstract` (+ its
   junk-list) into it. Functions that need `mailto`/`api_key` take them as
   parameters — the package does NOT read `.env` and does NOT define
   `MAILTO`/`OPENALEX_API_KEY`. Package uses stdlib `logging`; no dependency
   back into this repo. Deps: `requests`, `numpy`, `pandas`.
2. In this repo, turn the host modules into thin shims: `pipeline_io.py`,
   `pipeline_text.py`, `enrich_embeddings.py` import their moved symbols from
   `openalex_corpus` and re-export them (keep the names); `utils.py`'s
   existing re-export chain then works unchanged. At the call sites that pass
   `MAILTO`/`OPENALEX_API_KEY` into `retry_get`, thread the constants through
   as arguments (this repo still owns the constants). Add the package via
   `[tool.uv.sources]` (path source).

**Move B — relocate paper B's pipeline out.**
3. `git mv` (across repos) `scripts/het_build_corpus.py`, `het_embed.py`,
   `het_plot_overlap.py` and the committed `data/het/seeds.csv` into
   `polycentric_activity`. Point them at `openalex_corpus` (git source,
   pinned SHA) — they must NOT import from `climate-finance-het/scripts/` any
   more. Each supplies its own `mailto`/`api_key` from its own `.env`. Its
   model choice (MiniLM) stays there. Coordinate via a polycentric_activity
   ticket for the figure pipeline. After this, `data/het/` and the het
   scripts no longer exist in this repo.

**Move C — update the map.**
4. Update `.claude/rules/architecture.md`: **delete** the §"Companion
   pipelines" section (nothing companion remains here) and add a short note
   that the OpenAlex-crawl/canonical-text conventions live in
   `libs/openalex-corpus/`, consumed here via shims and by polycentric via
   git source.

## Test
Write the contract test FIRST (red): in the new package,
`tests/test_openalex.py` exercising `retry_get` (mock a 429→200 retry, and
assert `mailto`/`api_key` are read from the passed arguments, not the
environment), `reconstruct_abstract` (inverted-index dict → text),
`normalize_doi` (canonicalisation cases), and `build_text` +
`is_boilerplate_abstract` (row → text convention, incl. a boilerplate
abstract that gets skipped). This is the coverage that does not exist on the
cross-repo contract today.

Second red test, in THIS repo: a shim-resolution test that imports every
carved symbol via its old path (`from utils import ...`, `from pipeline_io
import retry_get`, etc.) and asserts it resolves to the package definition —
so a typo in a re-export fails loudly rather than silently breaking a
rarely-run script.

## Verification
- [x] `openalex-corpus` builds and its own test suite passes (PR #954/#956, 25/25).
- [x] This repo's check-fast is green AFTER the shims — no existing call site
      changed behaviour; equivalence + shim-resolution tests pass (PR #958,
      1127 passed).
- [x] `scripts/het_*.py` no longer exist in this repo (Move B). `data/het/seeds.csv`
      kept: `polycentric_activity` reads it by path.
- [~] MOOT: `polycentric_activity` does NOT consume the package — the overlap
      figure it fed was retired (author-confirmed) in favour of an
      embedding-free swim-lane figure; polycentric never imported this repo's
      `scripts/` (it only inlined `retry_get` on urllib).
- [x] `architecture.md` §"Companion pipelines" deleted; the package note added
      and updated to reflect the retirement (Move C).

## Invariants
- No behaviour change in this repo's own pipeline; the shims are API-preserving.
- `get_logger`, the constants `MAILTO`/`OPENALEX_API_KEY`, and the
  `pipeline_loaders` domain modules are NOT moved.
- The package never reads `.env` and has no dependency back into this repo
  (no import cycle).
- The 500KB plain-git limit and DVC conventions of this repo are untouched.

## Exit criteria (met — resolved as delete, not relocate)
- The convention layer lives in `libs/openalex-corpus/` and this repo consumes
  it via API-preserving shims (Move A, PRs #954/#956/#958). **No repo reaches
  into another's `scripts/` and no orphan companion scripts remain here** — the
  `het_*.py` trio is deleted (Move B), not relocated, because the overlap
  figure it produced was retired in favour of polycentric's own swim-lane
  figure. `architecture.md` §Companion pipelines is gone (Move C). The two live
  suites (package 25/25, this repo check-fast) are green; there is no
  "polycentric figure build" suite to gate — that path was retired, which is
  the whole reason the relocation collapsed into a deletion.

